\chapter{What is OpenFDEM}
\label{\detokenize{rst_about_project/intro:what-is-openfdem}}\label{\detokenize{rst_about_project/intro::doc}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
OpenFDEM aims to be a free finite and discrete element solver with object\sphinxhyphen{}oriented architecture for solving
\sphinxstylestrong{multiscale, multiphase, and multiphysics} (3M) problems. The applications are,
but not limited to, mechanical, thermal and fluid mechanics problems. The main features are:

\sphinxAtStartPar
\sphinxstylestrong{Modular \& Extensible FEM Kernel and DEM Kernel} (OPENFDEMlib)
\begin{itemize}
\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
\sphinxstylestrong{Fully extendable and portable} \sphinxhyphen{} The kernel can be extended in any “direction”. Adding new element types, new material models with any number of element types and internal history parameters, new boundary conditions (time\sphinxhyphen{}dependent, position\sphinxhyphen{}dependent, state\sphinxhyphen{}dependent, periodic and flow\sphinxhyphen{}in/out) or numerical algorithms (explicit and implicit) is possible, as well as the ability to add and manage arbitrary degrees of freedom is a matter of course. (It is not a Y\sphinxhyphen{}like code limited to constant\sphinxhyphen{}strain triangular elements, Q4 cohesive elements and triangle\sphinxhyphen{}triangle contacts; OpenFDEM is intended to be a more general FEM/DEM solver compatible with arbitrary scenarios.) Like other common open\sphinxhyphen{}source FEM solvers, the most important feature of OpenFDEM is its standardization and generality, which allows the continuum\sphinxhyphen{}discontinuum method to be used with more general scenarios.

\end{itemize}

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\capstart

\noindent\sphinxincludegraphics[scale=0.4]{{elementtype}.gif}
\caption{OpenFDEM supports 26 element types and 24 materials.}\label{\detokenize{rst_about_project/intro:id1}}\end{figure}

\begin{DUlineblock}{0em}
\item[] 
\end{DUlineblock}
\begin{itemize}
\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
\sphinxstylestrong{Flexible element definition} \sphinxhyphen{} OpenFDEM is not limited only to triangular elements, but allows Q4 cohesive element and triangle\sphinxhyphen{}triangle contact. OpenFDEM is a more general FEM/DEM solver can be compatible to arbitrary scenarios.

\end{itemize}

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\capstart

\noindent\sphinxincludegraphics[scale=0.5]{{elementshape}.png}
\caption{Quadratic elements are supported in OpenFDEM. Combined linear element (quadrilateral and triangle elements, left), quadratic quadrilateral element (middle) and refined linear quadrilateral element (right).}\label{\detokenize{rst_about_project/intro:id2}}\end{figure}

\begin{DUlineblock}{0em}
\item[] 
\end{DUlineblock}
\begin{itemize}
\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
\sphinxstylestrong{Highly accurate and reliable} \textendash{} The kernel can be extended in any “direction”. Adding new element types, new material models with any number of element types and internal history parameters, new boundary conditions (time\sphinxhyphen{}dependent, position\sphinxhyphen{}dependent, state\sphinxhyphen{}dependent, periodic and flow\sphinxhyphen{}in/out) or numerical algorithms (explicit and implicit) is possible, as well as the ability to add and manage arbitrary degrees of freedom is a matter of course. (It is not a Y\sphinxhyphen{}like code limited to constant\sphinxhyphen{}strain triangular elements, Q4 cohesive elements and triangle\sphinxhyphen{}triangle contacts; OpenFDEM is intended to be a more general FEM/DEM solver compatible with arbitrary scenarios.) Like other common open\sphinxhyphen{}source FEM solvers, the most important feature of OpenFDEM is its standardization and generality, which allows the continuum\sphinxhyphen{}discontinuum method to be used with more general scenarios.

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
\sphinxstylestrong{Friendly preprocessing interface} \sphinxhyphen{} The Gmsh is provided to easily create meshes from computer\sphinxhyphen{}aided design (CAD), geometry file and third\sphinxhyphen{}party commercial software. The built\sphinxhyphen{}in commands are accessible to create many basic geometries (e.g. rectangular, circle, ellipse, polygon, line and particles) and initial discontinuities (e.g. single joint, joint sets, DFNs and DFNs from image mapping). This built\sphinxhyphen{}in mesh module can quickly assess mesh quality and identify the local bad meshes which will be further optimized by swap, node insertion, node delete, element split techniques, automatically or manually. Meanwhile, for very complex geometric models, users can also import mesh files from third\sphinxhyphen{}party software. OpenFDEM supports importing standard mesh files, such as .msh, .inp, .stl, .dxf and .step, etc. Principally, the geometry file can be processed by Gmsh can also be done by OpenFDEM.

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
\sphinxstylestrong{Parallel processing support} \sphinxhyphen{} Most modules can be operated in parallel and very good performance scalability on various platforms. Instead of using no binary searching (NBS) contact method in OpenFDEM, a new element\sphinxhyphen{}wise contact searching algorithm with a complexity of O(NlogN) is proposed to make the contact searching process parallelable. The GPU acceleration will also be added shortly.

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
\sphinxstylestrong{Mesh adaptive analysis support} \textendash{} Local adaptive mesh refinement (lAMR) and global adaptive mesh refinement(gAMR) are provided in OpenFDEM for mesh optimization and accuracy enhancement. Based on different remeshing criteria, OpenFDEM supports various error estimations, such as primary unknown, internal variables mapping, high\sphinxhyphen{}accuracy internal variable interpolation and fast unbalance equilibrium after refinement. The AMR supports fracture path consistent before and after remeshing.

\end{itemize}

The realistic grain\sphinxhyphen{}based model (GBM) can be reproduced directly in the project by inputting the binary sample images. \chapter{Quick Start for Developers}
\label{\detokenize{rst_about_project/started:quick-start-for-developers}}\label{\detokenize{rst_about_project/started::doc}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
This is the source code of C/C++ based OpenFDEM project developed by Dr. Xiaofeng Li,
since 2017. This project is not limited to an FDEM solver for continuum\sphinxhyphen{}discontinuum problems,
but is also capable of solving particulate DEM, material point method and phasefield problems.

\sphinxAtStartPar
The project can be complied by Visual Studio (\textgreater{} 2015) and compatible with Windows 7, 10 or Linux\sphinxhyphen{}like systems.

\sphinxAtStartPar
Tutorial examples can be found in \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{..src\textbackslash{}test\textbackslash{}..}}. The main file is located at \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{src\textbackslash{}solve\textbackslash{}openfdem.cpp}}. OpenFDEM is run by
parsing the input file.

\sphinxAtStartPar
General steps to run OpenFDEM models:
\begin{enumerate}
\sphinxsetlistlabels{\arabic}{enumi}{enumii}{}{.}%
\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
Open \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{.sln}} project in \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{\textbackslash{}openfdem src\textbackslash{}of\textbackslash{}OpenFDEM\textbackslash{}OpenFDEM.sln}} by your local Visual Studio software.

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
Compile the project in Visual Studio  from the \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{src\textbackslash{}solve\textbackslash{}openfdem.cpp}} main file.

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
The executable code should be in \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{x64\textbackslash{}Release\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}(or \textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}Debug}}), be sure to keep the \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{.dll}} files in the same folder with \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{.exe}} file.

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
Drag the \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{.of}} file into the \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{.exe}} software then the model will starts to run, or use \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{openfdem example.of}} in terminal to run a model.

\end{enumerate}

\subsection{2.0 Codes}
\label{\detokenize{rst_tutorials/tutorial1_UCS_Test:codes}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
Please note that, all the setting in the example is based on the developer’s computer. You may need to change

\sphinxAtStartPar
To start with programming, create a new empty text file (later add the \sphinxtitleref{.of} extension). Begin writing the following commands:


\subsubsection{2.1 Initialize the model}
\label{\detokenize{rst_tutorials/tutorial1_UCS_Test:initialize-the-model}}\begin{enumerate}
\sphinxsetlistlabels{\arabic}{enumi}{enumii}{}{.}%
\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{Create a new run and clean up the old memories.}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{new}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{Set up the folder name to save your results. Here the folder name is set to be “result”.}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{set}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{result} \PYG{l+s+s2}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s+s2}{result}\PYG{l+s+s2}{\PYGZdq{}}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{Set the interval of logging in the log file. This example uses the default interval 2000 steps.}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{log}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{interval} \PYG{l+m+mi}{2000}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{Set the number of cores to be used for running this model.}
\begin{sphinxadmonition}{warning}{Warning:}
\sphinxAtStartPar
In this example, 15 cores will be used for running. To prevent the crushing of your computer, please
check your computer to fill in the number of cores you want to use from your computer. To check the number
of cores your computer has, you can go Task Manager \textgreater{} Performance \textgreater{} CPU \textgreater{} Cores. If nothing is set here,
serial computing will be used.
\end{sphinxadmonition}

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{set}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{omp} \PYG{l+m+mi}{15}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\end{enumerate}


\subsubsection{2.2 Create the geometry and the mesh}
\label{\detokenize{rst_tutorials/tutorial1_UCS_Test:create-the-geometry-and-the-mesh}}\begin{enumerate}
\sphinxsetlistlabels{\arabic}{enumi}{enumii}{}{.}%
\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{See Figure 1 for the UCS test setup and draw the corresponding geometry.}
\begin{sphinxadmonition}{note}{Note:}\begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{The following three methods can be used to create the geometry:}\begin{enumerate}
\sphinxsetlistlabels{\arabic}{enumii}{enumiii}{}{.}%
\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
xmin x\_minvalue  xmax x\_maxvalue  ymin y\_minvalue  ymax y\_maxvalue

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
x {[}minvalue, maxvalue{]} y {[}minvalue, maxvalue{]}

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
{[}x\_minvalue, x\_maxvalue, y\_minvalue, y\_maxvalue{]}

\end{enumerate}

\end{description}

\sphinxAtStartPar
This example used all three methods for demonstration. Users may choose any format to create geometris.
\end{sphinxadmonition}

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{geometry}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{square} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{rock}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}} \PYG{n}{xmin} \PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{l+m+mf}{25e\PYGZhy{}3} \PYG{n}{xmax} \PYG{l+m+mf}{25e\PYGZhy{}3}  \PYG{n}{ymin} \PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{l+m+mf}{50e\PYGZhy{}3} \PYG{n}{ymax} \PYG{l+m+mf}{50e\PYGZhy{}3} 
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{geometry}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{square} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{up}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}} \PYG{n}{x} \PYG{p}{[}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{l+m+mf}{35e\PYGZhy{}3}\PYG{p}{,} \PYG{l+m+mf}{35e\PYGZhy{}3}\PYG{p}{]} \PYG{n}{y} \PYG{p}{[}\PYG{l+m+mf}{50e\PYGZhy{}3}\PYG{p}{,} \PYG{l+m+mf}{55e\PYGZhy{}3}\PYG{p}{]}
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{geometry}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{square} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{down}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}} \PYG{p}{[}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{l+m+mf}{35e\PYGZhy{}3}  \PYG{l+m+mf}{35e\PYGZhy{}3}  \PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{l+m+mf}{55e\PYGZhy{}3} \PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{l+m+mf}{50e\PYGZhy{}3}\PYG{p}{]} 
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{Set the mesh size of the geometry and insert cohesive interfaces.}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{geometry}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{mesh}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{size} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{default}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}} \PYG{l+m+mf}{0.8e\PYGZhy{}3}
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{geometry}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{mesh} \PYG{n}{delaunay} 
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{mesh}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{insert} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{rock}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\end{enumerate}


\subsubsection{2.3 Assign Material Properties}
\label{\detokenize{rst_tutorials/tutorial1_UCS_Test:assign-material-properties}}\begin{enumerate}
\sphinxsetlistlabels{\arabic}{enumi}{enumii}{}{.}%
\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{Set the material properties. For this test, the example uses the elastic constitutive model and assigned material for CZM and contact.}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{mat}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{element} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{default}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}} \PYG{n}{elastic} \PYG{n}{den} \PYG{l+m+mi}{2700} \PYG{n}{E} \PYG{l+m+mf}{30e9} \PYG{n}{v} \PYG{l+m+mf}{0.3} \PYG{n}{damp} \PYG{l+m+mf}{1.0}
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{mat}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{cohesive} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{default}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}} \PYG{n}{EM} \PYG{n}{ten} \PYG{l+m+mf}{1e6} \PYG{n}{coh} \PYG{l+m+mf}{3e6} \PYG{n}{fric} \PYG{l+m+mf}{0.3} \PYG{n}{GI} \PYG{l+m+mi}{10} \PYG{n}{GII} \PYG{l+m+mi}{50} 
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{mat}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{contact} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{default}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}} \PYG{n}{MC} \PYG{n}{fric} \PYG{l+m+mf}{0.3}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\end{enumerate}


\subsubsection{2.4 Create Groups and Assign Boundary Conditions}
\label{\detokenize{rst_tutorials/tutorial1_UCS_Test:create-groups-and-assign-boundary-conditions}}\begin{enumerate}
\sphinxsetlistlabels{\arabic}{enumi}{enumii}{}{.}%
\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{Group the nodes to prepare for the next step.}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{group}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{nodal}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{from}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{element} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{up}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{up}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{group}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{nodal}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{from}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{element} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{down}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{down}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{Assign the nodal boundaries. For uniaxial test, top and bottom platens are moving toward the sample the compress the sample, so platens are not moving in the x direction and moving with 0.05 m/s in the y direction.}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{boundary}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{nodal}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{velocity} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{up}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}} \PYG{n}{x} \PYG{l+m+mf}{0.0} \PYG{n}{y} \PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{l+m+mf}{0.05} 
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{boundary}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{nodal}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{velocity} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{down}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}} \PYG{n}{x} \PYG{l+m+mf}{0.0} \PYG{n}{y} \PYG{l+m+mf}{0.05} 
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\end{enumerate}


\subsubsection{2.5 Set the Outputs}
\label{\detokenize{rst_tutorials/tutorial1_UCS_Test:set-the-outputs}}\begin{enumerate}
\sphinxsetlistlabels{\arabic}{enumi}{enumii}{}{.}%
\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{Set the output interval to be every 50000 steps and output all fields variables and fracture variables. Control the output interval to a reasonable size could shorten the computation time but get a good understanding of the model.}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{history}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{pv}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{interval} \PYG{l+m+mi}{5000}
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{history}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{pv}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{field} \PYG{n}{default}
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{history}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{pv}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{fracture} \PYG{n}{default}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{Timestep can be fixed to 5e\sphinxhyphen{}9 in this example to accelerate the calculation in this example, but the default time step is recommended to use.}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{timestep} \PYG{n}{fix} \PYG{l+m+mf}{5e\PYGZhy{}9}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{The program will run 500000 steps in total. In other words, it will output 10 files for reference.}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{step} \PYG{l+m+mi}{500000}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{Finalize the model and clear all the temporary memories.}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{finalize}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
Save the notepad and double click the .of file to run the program.

\end{enumerate}

\PYG{c+c1}{\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{} create mesh \PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}}
\PYG{c+c1}{\PYGZsh{} Create a box having the group tag \PYGZsq{}rock\PYGZsq{}, the box is defined by the minimum and maximum }
\PYG{c+c1}{\PYGZsh{} coordinations of each edge.}

\section{Tutorial 2: UCS model from Gmsh}
\label{\detokenize{rst_tutorials/tutorial2_UCS_with_Gmsh:tutorial-2-ucs-model-from-gmsh}}\label{\detokenize{rst_tutorials/tutorial2_UCS_with_Gmsh::doc}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
OpenFDEM also allows users to import common mesh files such as .inp files, .msh files, and .geo files to run the model.
This example will review how to setup a uniaxial compressive test example with output from Gmsh software.

\sphinxAtStartPar
\sphinxstylestrong{Runtime}: \textless{}10 min on i9 8\sphinxhyphen{}core Windows 10 Machine

\sphinxAtStartPar

\noindent{\hspace*{\fill}\sphinxincludegraphics[width=800\sphinxpxdimen]{{ucs_example}.png}\hspace*{\fill}}

\begin{enumerate}
\sphinxsetlistlabels{\arabic}{enumi}{enumii}{}{.}%
\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
A user defined command in OpenFDEM to create mesh automatically

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
Importing a \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{.geo}} file

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
Importing a \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{.msh}} file

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
Mesh developed from other commercial softwares, including \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{.inp}}, \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{.dxf}}, \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{.fdem}}, \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{.tess}} (for grain\sphinxhyphen{}based model only) and \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{.jpg}} (for grain\sphinxhyphen{}based module and DFN module only).

\end{enumerate}
\end{sphinxadmonition}

\section{Tutorial 3: Create Uniaxial Compression Test with Quadrangle Element}
\label{\detokenize{rst_tutorials/tutorial3_UCS_Test_with_Quadrangle_Elements:tutorial-3-create-uniaxial-compression-test-with-quadrangle-element}}\label{\detokenize{rst_tutorials/tutorial3_UCS_Test_with_Quadrangle_Elements::doc}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
By default, triangle elements will be used in the mesh and model. However, OpenFDEM also supports
the quadrangle elements.


\subsection{1.0 Code}
\label{\detokenize{rst_tutorials/tutorial3_UCS_Test_with_Quadrangle_Elements:code}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
To run the model with quadrangle elements, users just need to add the following line after setting
up the mesh size and before creating the mesh.

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{geometry}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{recombine} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{rock}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\subsubsection{2.1 Initialize the model}
\label{\detokenize{rst_tutorials/tutorial5_In_Situ_Stress:initialize-the-model}}\begin{enumerate}
\sphinxsetlistlabels{\arabic}{enumi}{enumii}{}{.}%
\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{Create a new run and clean up the old memories.}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{new}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{Set up the folder name to save your results. Here the folder name is set to be “result”.}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{set}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{result} \PYG{l+s+s2}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s+s2}{result}\PYG{l+s+s2}{\PYGZdq{}}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{Set the number of cores to be used for running this model.}
\begin{sphinxadmonition}{warning}{Warning:}
\sphinxAtStartPar
In this example, 15 cores will be used for running. To prevent the crushing of your computer, please
check your computer to fill in the number of cores you want to use from your computer. To check the number
of cores your computer has, you can go Task Manager \textgreater{} Performance \textgreater{} CPU \textgreater{} Cores. If nothing is set here,
serial computing will be used.
\end{sphinxadmonition}

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{set}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{omp} \PYG{l+m+mi}{15}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\end{enumerate}


\subsubsection{2.2 Create the geometry and the mesh}
\label{\detokenize{rst_tutorials/tutorial5_In_Situ_Stress:create-the-geometry-and-the-mesh}}\begin{enumerate}
\sphinxsetlistlabels{\arabic}{enumi}{enumii}{}{.}%
\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{See Figure 1, we will create a square rock model with a 0.05 m radius hole at the center of the rock.}
\begin{sphinxadmonition}{note}{Note:}
\sphinxAtStartPar
Circles in OpenFDEM are defined by four values: x coordinate, y coordinate, radius and the number of segments. Users can define a circle by entering \sphinxstylestrong{{[}x\_value y\_value radius \#\_of\_segements{]}}.
\end{sphinxadmonition}

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{geometry}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{square} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{rock}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}} \PYG{p}{[}\PYG{l+m+mi}{0} \PYG{l+m+mi}{1} \PYG{l+m+mi}{0} \PYG{l+m+mi}{1}\PYG{p}{]}
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{geometry}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{cut}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{circle} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{hole}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{rock}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}} \PYG{p}{[}\PYG{l+m+mf}{0.5} \PYG{l+m+mf}{0.5} \PYG{l+m+mf}{0.05} \PYG{l+m+mi}{100}\PYG{p}{]}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{Set the mesh size and the default method to create the mesh}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{geometry}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{mesh}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{size} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{default}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}} \PYG{l+m+mf}{0.03}
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{geometry}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{mesh} \PYG{n}{auto}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{Group the elements which will be excavated later.}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{group}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{element} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{excavation}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}} \PYG{n+nb}{range} \PYG{n}{circle}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{o+ow}{in} \PYG{p}{[}\PYG{l+m+mf}{0.5} \PYG{l+m+mf}{0.5} \PYG{l+m+mf}{0.05}\PYG{p}{]}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\end{enumerate}


\subsubsection{2.3 Assign Material Properties}
\label{\detokenize{rst_tutorials/tutorial5_In_Situ_Stress:assign-material-properties}}\begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{Set the material properties as shown below.}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{mat}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{element} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{default}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}} \PYG{n}{elastic} \PYG{n}{den} \PYG{l+m+mi}{2700} \PYG{n}{E} \PYG{l+m+mf}{30e9} \PYG{n}{v} \PYG{l+m+mf}{0.3} \PYG{n}{damp} \PYG{l+m+mf}{1.0}
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{mat}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{contact} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{default}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}} \PYG{n}{MC} \PYG{n}{fric} \PYG{l+m+mf}{0.3}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}


\subsubsection{2.4 Group the Edges}
\label{\detokenize{rst_tutorials/tutorial5_In_Situ_Stress:group-the-edges}}\begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{Group the four boundaries of the model for applying the in\sphinxhyphen{}situ stresses and boundary conditions later.}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{group}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{edge} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{bottom}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}} \PYG{n+nb}{range} \PYG{n}{plane}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{on} \PYG{p}{[}\PYG{l+m+mf}{0.0} \PYG{l+m+mf}{0.0} \PYG{l+m+mf}{1.0} \PYG{l+m+mf}{0.0}\PYG{p}{]}
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{group}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{edge} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{up}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}} \PYG{n+nb}{range} \PYG{n}{plane}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{on} \PYG{p}{[}\PYG{l+m+mf}{0.0} \PYG{l+m+mf}{1.0} \PYG{l+m+mf}{1.0} \PYG{l+m+mf}{1.0}\PYG{p}{]}
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{group}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{edge} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{left}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}} \PYG{n+nb}{range} \PYG{n}{plane}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{on} \PYG{p}{[}\PYG{l+m+mf}{0.0} \PYG{l+m+mf}{0.0} \PYG{l+m+mf}{0.0} \PYG{l+m+mf}{1.0}\PYG{p}{]}
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{group}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{edge} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{right}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}} \PYG{n+nb}{range} \PYG{n}{plane}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{on} \PYG{p}{[}\PYG{l+m+mf}{1.0} \PYG{l+m+mf}{0.0} \PYG{l+m+mf}{1.0} \PYG{l+m+mf}{1.0}\PYG{p}{]}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}


\subsubsection{2.5 Assign Boundary Conditions}
\label{\detokenize{rst_tutorials/tutorial5_In_Situ_Stress:assign-boundary-conditions}}\begin{enumerate}
\sphinxsetlistlabels{\arabic}{enumi}{enumii}{}{.}%
\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{For this example, 30 MPa compressive stress in the xx direction and 5 MPa compressive stresses in the yy direction are assigned to the rock.}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{boundary}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{element}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{stress} \PYG{p}{[}\PYG{n}{rock}\PYG{p}{]} \PYG{n}{xx} \PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{l+m+mf}{30e6} \PYG{n}{xy} \PYG{l+m+mf}{0.0} \PYG{n}{yy} \PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{l+m+mf}{5e6}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{To quickly balance the model, absorbing boundary conditions are assigned to four boundaries in the model.}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{boundary}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{edge}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{viscous} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{up}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}  \PYG{n}{normal} \PYG{n}{shear}
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{boundary}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{edge}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{viscous} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{bottom}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}  \PYG{n}{normal} \PYG{n}{shear}
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{boundary}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{edge}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{viscous} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{right}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}  \PYG{n}{normal} \PYG{n}{shear}
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{boundary}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{edge}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{viscous} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{left}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}  \PYG{n}{normal} \PYG{n}{shear}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\end{enumerate}


\subsubsection{2.6 Set the Outputs}
\label{\detokenize{rst_tutorials/tutorial5_In_Situ_Stress:set-the-outputs}}\begin{enumerate}
\sphinxsetlistlabels{\arabic}{enumi}{enumii}{}{.}%
\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{Set the output interval to be every 2000 steps and output all fields variables and fracture variables. Control the output interval to a reasonable size could shorten the computation time but get a good understanding of the model.}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{history}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{pv}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{interval} \PYG{l+m+mi}{2000}
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{history}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{pv}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{field} \PYG{n}{default}
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{history}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{pv}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{fracture} \PYG{n}{default}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{In this step, model will first achieve the equilibrium without excavation under in\sphinxhyphen{}situ stresses state. The result of velocity or kinematic ratio should be less than 1e\sphinxhyphen{}5.}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{step} \PYG{l+m+mi}{50000}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{Insert CZM after achieve the equlibrium of in\sphinxhyphen{}situ stresses}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{mesh}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{insert} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{default}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{mat}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{cohesive} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{default}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}} \PYG{n}{EM} \PYG{n}{ten} \PYG{l+m+mf}{1e6} \PYG{n}{coh} \PYG{l+m+mf}{20e6} \PYG{n}{fric} \PYG{l+m+mf}{0.8} \PYG{n}{GI} \PYG{l+m+mi}{2} \PYG{n}{GII} \PYG{l+m+mi}{40} 
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{One step excavation. Remove the elements in the “excavation” group.}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{boundary}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{excavation} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{excavation}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{Clear the absorbing boundaries}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{boundary}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{edge}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{clear} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{up}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{boundary}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{edge}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{clear} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{bottom}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{boundary}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{edge}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{clear} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{right}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{boundary}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{edge}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{clear} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{left}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{Add pressures at the external boundaries}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{boundary}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{edge}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{pressure} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{right}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}  \PYG{n}{normal} \PYG{l+m+mf}{30e6}  
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{boundary}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{edge}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{pressure} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{up}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}  \PYG{n}{normal} \PYG{l+m+mf}{5e6}  
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{boundary}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{edge}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{pressure} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{bottom}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}  \PYG{n}{normal} \PYG{l+m+mf}{5e6}  
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{boundary}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{edge}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{pressure} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{left}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}} \PYG{n}{normal} \PYG{l+m+mf}{30e6} 
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{The program will run 500000 steps in total. In other words, it will output 25 files for reference.}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{step} \PYG{l+m+mi}{500000}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\item {} \begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{Finalize the model and clear all the temporary memories.}
\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{of}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{finalize}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\end{description}

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
Save the notepad and double click the .of file to run the program.

\end{enumerate}

\subsection{of.solve}
\label{\detokenize{rst_user_guide/General/of.solve:of-solve}}\label{\detokenize{rst_user_guide/General/of.solve::doc}}

\sphinxAtStartPar
\sphinxstylestrong{(Mandatory)} Assign the mechanical ratio as the iteration threshold to exit the running.
The double value \(\zeta\) is the ratio of the total maximum unbalance force to the total
force. Generally, the ratio less than 1.0e\sphinxhyphen{}5 can be considered as the equilibrium state.
This command is important to determine the equilibrium state in in\sphinxhyphen{}situ stress equilibrium
or static problems.

\sphinxAtStartPar
\(\zeta = \frac{\sum^n_{i=1}\sqrt{\bar{f_i}}}{\sum^n_{i=1}\sum^n_{j=1}\sqrt{f_{i,j}}}\), \(\bar{f_i}\) is the unbalanced force on
node \(i\). \(j\) are types of the nodal forces. \(f_{i,j}\) is the \(j\) th type force on node \(i\).
